Class BramsprChecker

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.AbstractParseTreeVisitor<T>

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    BramsprVisitor<Suit>, org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.ParseTreeVisitor<Suit>

    public class BramsprChecker
extends BramsprBaseVisitor<Suit>
    This class is responsible for the context checking of Bramspr programs. Intended to be used in conjunction with BramsprLexer, BramsprParser and BramsprCompiler. The context checking starts with feeding a parse tree as generated by BramsprParser to check(ParseTree). The program then gets context-checked by recursive calls to various visit-methods this class contains. Afterwards, the parse tree, now augmented with context information stored in ParseTreeProperty-objects, can be fed to BramsprCompiler for Java Bytecode generation.

      • parseTreeDecoration

        private org.antlr.v4.runtime.tree.ParseTreeProperty<Symbol> parseTreeDecoration
        The object that maps symbol-objects to parse tree nodes. As the parse tree node of an applied occurrence of an identifier is visited, it is mapped to the symbol-object that was created when the parse tree node of its binding occurrence was visited. This object is returned by check(ParseTree) and is later used by BramsprCompiler during object code generation.

      • visitCompositeDeclaration

        public Suit visitCompositeDeclaration(BramsprParser.CompositeDeclarationContext ctx)
        Handles the context checking of a Composite-Declaration. A Composite-Declaration is confined to the following context rules:

        1. a composite type with the same identifier must have not already been declared in this scope;
        2. all fields must have a unique identifier.

      • visitCompositeLiteral

        public Suit visitCompositeLiteral(BramsprParser.CompositeLiteralContext ctx)
        Handles the context checking of a Composite-Literal. A Composite-Literal is confined to the following context rules:

        1. the denoted composite type must have been declared;
        2. assigned fields must be fields of the denoted composite type;
        3. each of the denoted composite type's fields must be assigned a value;
        4. a field must not be assigned a value more than once;
        5. each assigned value's type must have the same type as the field it is being assigned to;
        6. the Composite-Literal is of the type that the Identifier denotes;
        7. the Composite-Literal is constant if all of the assigned values are constant.

        Specified by:
        visitCompositeLiteral in interface BramsprVisitor<Suit>
        Overrides:
        visitCompositeLiteral in class BramsprBaseVisitor<Suit>
        Parameters:
        ctx - The context object associated with the parse tree node of this Composite-Literal.
        Returns:
        The suit of the Composite-Literal or Suit.ERROR in case of a context error.

      • visitPotentialEnumerationLiteral

        public Suit visitPotentialEnumerationLiteral(BramsprParser.PotentialEnumerationLiteralContext ctx)
        Handles the context checking of a potential-Enumeration-Literal. A potential-Enumeration-Literal can, depending on the context, indeed be an enumeration literal, or actually a field access on a variable of composite type. This method first tries to resolve the left-hand identifier in variableSymbolTable. If that gives no result, it resolves it in enumerationSymbolTable. If the identifier turns out to be declared as a variable, this method checks the context rules for a Field-access (see visitFieldAccess). If the identifier matches an enumerated type instead, the method checks the context rules as for an explicit-Enumeration-Literal (see visitExplicitEnumerationLiteral).
        Specified by:
        visitPotentialEnumerationLiteral in interface BramsprVisitor<Suit>
        Overrides:
        visitPotentialEnumerationLiteral in class BramsprBaseVisitor<Suit>
        Parameters:
        ctx - The context object associated with the parse tree node of this potential-Enumeration-Literal.
        Returns:
        The suit of the potential-Enumeration-Literal or Suit.ERROR in case of a context error.
        See Also:
        #visitExplicitEnumerationLiteral(ExplicitEnumerationLiteralContext)
